<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="99" pageId="2" pageNumber="98" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1004,2007]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1365,1390]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98">Description</emphasis>
. Body of medium length (
<quantity box="[652,782,1365,1389]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.55" metricValueMax="1.9" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="2" pageNumber="98" unit="mm" value="15.5" valueMax="19.0" valueMin="12.0">12â€“19 mm</quantity>
); dorso-ventrally flat head and abdomen. Short setae on head, pronotum and legs; 
<collectionCode box="[453,498,1402,1425]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98">TIII</collectionCode>
very hairy. Head wider than high in front view; vertex completely flat; face and vertex making an obtuse angle in lateral view. Fastigium wider than scape. Eyes bulging, ellipsoidal in shape. Median ocellus dorsal in position and larger than lateral ocelli; ocelli arranged in triangle, the distance between lateral ocelli twice the distance between lateral and median ocelli. Epistemal suture convex and very deep; area between antennal pit and epistemal suture bulged with deep concavity in the middle. Clypeus slightly bulging. Maxillary palpi short; 
<number box="[402,416,1584,1608]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98" value="3.0">3</number>
rd, 
<number box="[443,457,1584,1608]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98" value="4.0">4</number>
th and 
<number box="[523,537,1583,1608]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98" value="5.0">5</number>
th joints variable in length, 
<number box="[836,850,1584,1608]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98" value="4.0">4</number>
th equal to or longer than 
<number box="[1130,1144,1584,1608]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98" value="3.0">3</number>
rd and 
<number box="[1211,1225,1583,1608]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98" value="5.0">5</number>
th; dorsal side of 
<number box="[1410,1424,1583,1608]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98" value="5.0">5</number>
th joint concave; distal end angular. Pronotum transverse and wider than head, narrowing anteriorly; DD anterior margin slightly concave and raised; DD posterior margin convex; LL very short, obliquely truncated posteriorly. TI with large inner tympanum; small outer tympanum (absent in Indian species); one pair of ventral apical spurs; inner apical spur twice longer than outer. TII inflated; with a pair of ventral apical spurs. 
<collectionCode box="[1076,1121,1728,1751]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98">TIII</collectionCode>
with 
<number box="[1184,1198,1728,1752]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98" value="3.0">3</number>
pairs of apical spurs; inner ventral spur the smallest; median inner spur the longest, twice as long as median outer apical spur. 
<collectionCode box="[1391,1436,1765,1788]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98">TIII</collectionCode>
dorsally flattened, with strong lateral margins, 
<number box="[670,684,1800,1824]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98" value="2.0">2</number>
inner and 
<number box="[801,843,1800,1824]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2â€“3</number>
outer subapical spurs. Basitarsomeres III higher than wide; furrowed dorsally with series of spines on either side. FW and HW present in both males and females. Cerci very thick and long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1004,2007]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1436,151,899]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="99" pageId="2" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,267,1908,1933]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98">Male.</emphasis>
FW and HW upto or sometimes longer than abdomen; HW longer than FW. FW with all stridulatory structures: file without teeth on ascending part; harp with 
<number box="[815,856,1943,1968]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98" value="6.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="6.0">6â€“7</number>
veins; mirror divided by two veins and located on anterior half; additional vein between mirror and 
<number box="[705,719,1983,2007]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98" value="1.0">1</number>
st chord making anterior angle of mirror flat (
<figureCitation box="[1223,1290,1982,2007]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1816,1838]" captionTargetBox="[195,1380,210,1761]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[177,1401,193,1778]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pteroplistes species: (A â€“ C) Maxillary palpi joints of (A) P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp. (B) P. platycleis Bolivar, 1900 (1899), (C) P. kervasae Jaiswara n. sp.; (D â€“ F, L, M) Male and female FWs of (D) P. platycleis Bolivar, 1900 (1899), female, (E, F) P. kervasae Jaiswara n. sp. male and female, (L, M) P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp. male and female; (G, K) male supra anal plates of (G) P. kervasae Jaiswara n. sp. and (K) P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp.; (H, N) male subgenital plates of (H) of P. kervasae Jaiswara n. sp. in dorsal (i) and lateral view (ii), (N) of P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp. in dorsal (i) and lateral view (ii); (J, O) subgenital plate of females, (J) of P. kervasae Jaiswara n. sp. and (O) of P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp.; (I) female copulatory papilla ventral (i) and dorsal (ii) view of P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227312/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="98">
Fig. 
<number box="[1275,1290,1983,2007]" pageId="2" pageNumber="98" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
E, L). Mirror cell separated from apical field by a narrow, transverse undivided cell. Other venation: CuP thicker than CuA and extending upto 
<number box="[326,340,191,215]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99" value="2.0">2</number>
nd or 
<number box="[392,406,191,215]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99" value="3.0">3</number>
rd harp vein; two short horizontal veins between mirror and CuA. Apical field long with 
<number box="[1394,1436,190,215]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99" value="4.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="4.0">4â€“5</number>
cell alignments. Lateral field with 
<number box="[556,626,227,251]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99" value="15.0" valueMax="19.0" valueMin="11.0">11â€“19</number>
oblique veins. Supra-anal plate with a median structure more or less subdivided and prolonged into a pair of dorsal spine like structure, diverging from common base. Subgenital plate high and wide, apically not truncated (
<figureCitation box="[582,649,298,323]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1816,1838]" captionTargetBox="[195,1380,210,1761]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[177,1401,193,1778]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pteroplistes species: (A â€“ C) Maxillary palpi joints of (A) P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp. (B) P. platycleis Bolivar, 1900 (1899), (C) P. kervasae Jaiswara n. sp.; (D â€“ F, L, M) Male and female FWs of (D) P. platycleis Bolivar, 1900 (1899), female, (E, F) P. kervasae Jaiswara n. sp. male and female, (L, M) P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp. male and female; (G, K) male supra anal plates of (G) P. kervasae Jaiswara n. sp. and (K) P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp.; (H, N) male subgenital plates of (H) of P. kervasae Jaiswara n. sp. in dorsal (i) and lateral view (ii), (N) of P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp. in dorsal (i) and lateral view (ii); (J, O) subgenital plate of females, (J) of P. kervasae Jaiswara n. sp. and (O) of P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp.; (I) female copulatory papilla ventral (i) and dorsal (ii) view of P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227312/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">
Fig. 
<number box="[634,649,299,323]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
N).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,899]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,379,334,359]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">Male genitalia.</emphasis>
Pseudepiphallic sclerite transverse with a pair of dorsal lophi (
<figureCitation box="[1108,1178,334,359]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1923,1945]" captionTargetBox="[173,1415,193,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[153,1433,193,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Male genitalia in dorsal, ventral and lateral view of (A â€“ C) P. kervasae Jaiswara n. sp.; (D â€“ F) P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp. Abbreviations, see Material and Methods. Scale 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227314/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">
Fig. 
<number box="[1163,1178,335,359]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
A, D); pseudepiphallic apodeme and parameres absent. Rami often long, wide sub-anteriorly and irregular in shape; rami connected to pseudepiphallic sclerite posteriorly. Ectophallic fold long, partly membranous and with a pair of sclerotized upper processes (ectophallic hooks) (
<figureCitation box="[511,583,442,467]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1923,1945]" captionTargetBox="[173,1415,193,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[153,1433,193,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Male genitalia in dorsal, ventral and lateral view of (A â€“ C) P. kervasae Jaiswara n. sp.; (D â€“ F) P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp. Abbreviations, see Material and Methods. Scale 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227314/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">
Fig. 
<number box="[568,583,443,467]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
A, F). Anterior part of endophallic cavity sclerotized and with a pair of endophallic hooks (
<figureCitation box="[371,439,478,503]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1923,1945]" captionTargetBox="[173,1415,193,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[153,1433,193,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Male genitalia in dorsal, ventral and lateral view of (A â€“ C) P. kervasae Jaiswara n. sp.; (D â€“ F) P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp. Abbreviations, see Material and Methods. Scale 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227314/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">
Fig. 
<number box="[423,439,479,503]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
B, E).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,899]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,293,514,539]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">Female.</emphasis>
FW variable in length, slightly overlapping; venation made of equally strong longitudinal and transverse veins, delimiting many squared to diamond-shaped cells. Ovipositor flat laterally, smooth and sword like. Subgenital plate short or very short, wider than long and indented apically.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,899]" box="[199,1140,622,648]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,403,622,647]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">Female genitalia.</emphasis>
Copulatory papilla very flat, variously sclerotized; apex rounded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,899]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,658,683]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">Coloration.</emphasis>
Body rufous to dark brown. Head rufous and dark brown mixed. Pronotum LL brown; DD light brown. Legs yellowish; femora with brown dots; FI and FII with sub distal brown rings. Female forewing veins pigmented (
<figureCitation box="[284,347,730,755]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1904,1926]" captionTargetBox="[180,1399,203,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1432,195,1892]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pteroplistes species from Western Ghats, India. (A) P. platycleis Bolivar, 1900 (1899), (B â€“ C) P. kervasae Jaiswara n. sp. male and female, (D â€“ E) P. masinagudi Jaiswara n. sp. male and female. Scale 5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227311/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">
Fig. 
<number box="[337,347,731,755]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
A, C, E).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,899]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,766,791]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">Habitat.</emphasis>
From observations of males and females, 
<taxonomicName authority="Jaiswara" authorityName="Jaiswara" box="[774,1007,766,791]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Pteroplistes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kervasae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[774,901,766,791]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">P. kervasae</emphasis>
Jaiswara
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1019,1082,766,791]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1019,1082,766,791]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Jaiswara" authorityName="Jaiswara" box="[1137,1402,766,791]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Pteroplistes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="masinagudi" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1137,1296,766,791]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">P. masinagudi</emphasis>
Jaiswara
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="3" pageNumber="99" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="99">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
are nocturnal crickets hiding under raised barks during the day; they are active high on tree trunks; males were observed singing at 
<quantity box="[385,480,838,863]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="99" unit="m" value="2.25" valueMax="2.5" valueMin="2.0">2â€“2.5 m</quantity>
high on small trees near main branch forks. These observations on Indian species confirm Gorochovâ€™s (
<number box="[392,451,875,899]" pageId="3" pageNumber="99" value="2004.0">2004</number>
) data.
</paragraph>
